<paragraph id="A263AB7BFFC81B71D8D4FC85FC6EB08E" blockId="1.[151,1436,885,1486]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D8D4FC85FE66B6CE" bold="true" box="[151,466,885,910]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Justification of synonymy.</emphasis>
Our decision follows the same rationale proposed by Sharma 
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DCDFFC86FB62B6CD" box="[1180,1238,885,909]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DCA5FC86FA96B6CE" box="[1254,1314,886,910]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2011.0">2011</number>
), based on evidence from a molecular phylogeny which indicates that the Indo-Pacific 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DBAEFC69FBC7B6F2" box="[1005,1139,921,946]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Zalmoxidae</taxonomicName>
constitute a monophyletic group (Sharma &amp; Giribet 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D999FC4EFDA2B696" box="[474,534,958,982]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2012.0">2012</number>
), thus disfavoring monotypic genera that would render 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DC86FC4DFA98B695" box="[1221,1324,957,981]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DC86FC4DFA98B695" box="[1221,1324,957,981]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
para- or polyphyletic. The habitus of 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D994FC12FDC6B6B9" box="[471,626,993,1017]" class="Arachnida" family="Samoidae" genus="Fijicolana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D994FC12FDC6B6B9" box="[471,626,993,1017]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">F. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is zalmoxid-like, with a pyriform dorsal scutum, and remarkably similar to that of the New Caledonian species 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DA21FBF5FB99B15E" authority="Roewer, 1912" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1912" box="[610,1069,1029,1054]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neocaledonicus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DA21FBF5FC36B15D" box="[610,898,1029,1053]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis neocaledonicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C64DD68AFFC81B71DBCEFBF6FB99B15E" author="Roewer" box="[909,1069,1030,1054]" pageId="1" pageNumber="260" refString="Roewer, C. F. (1912) Die Familien der Assamiiden und Phalangodiden der Opiliones-Laniatores (= Assamiden, Dampetriden, Phalangodiden, Epedaniden, Biantiden, Zalmoxiden, Samoiden, Palpipediden anderer Autoren). Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, Berlin, Abteilung A, 78 (3), 1 - 242." type="journal article" year="1912">
Roewer, 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DBB6FBF6FB99B15E" box="[1013,1069,1030,1054]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="1912.0">1912</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DC2FFBF5FF67B102" authority="Sharma, 2012" authorityName="Sharma" authorityYear="2012" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendax">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DC2FFBF5FA80B15D" box="[1132,1332,1029,1053]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis mendax</emphasis>
Sharma, 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D8D4FBDAFF67B102" box="[151,211,1066,1090]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</taxonomicName>
. Additionally, the well-marked bulla, male genital morphology, and enlarged metatarsus III are very similar to other 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D894FBBDFE8AB125" box="[215,318,1101,1125]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D894FBBDFE8AB125" box="[215,318,1101,1125]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (see below). The only two morphological features discordant with the most recent diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D8FAFB81FE94B1C9" box="[185,288,1137,1161]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D8FAFB81FE94B1C9" box="[185,288,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Sharma 
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D980FB82FE4BB1C9" box="[451,511,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DA4AFB82FDF6B1CA" box="[521,578,1138,1162]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2011.0">2011</number>
) are the presence of five tarsomeres on leg IV (rather than six in typical 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D8D4FB65FF4AB1ED" box="[151,254,1173,1197]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D8D4FB65FF4AB1ED" box="[151,254,1173,1197]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species) and the presence of tarsal scopulae on legs III and IV. Sharma 
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DC6AFB66FBD6B1ED" box="[1065,1122,1173,1197]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DC31FB66FB18B1EE" box="[1138,1196,1174,1198]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2011.0">2011</number>
) stated that the tarsal formula for 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D967FB49FE3FB191" box="[292,395,1209,1233]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D967FB49FE3FB191" box="[292,395,1209,1233]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D9F1FB4AFE77B192" box="[434,451,1210,1234]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="3.0">3</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D991FB49FDB4B192" box="[466,512,1209,1234]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="7.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="5.0">5–9</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DA4EFB49FDAAB192" box="[525,542,1209,1234]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="5.0">5</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DA6EFB49FD89B192" box="[557,573,1209,1234]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="6.0">6</number>
, however a re-examination of all tarsal formulae described for the species currently placed in 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D933FB2DFE63B1B5" box="[368,471,1245,1269]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D933FB2DFE63B1B5" box="[368,471,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows greater variation in all legs: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DB24FB2EFC21B1B6" box="[871,917,1246,1270]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DBDCFB2EFC79B1B6" box="[927,973,1246,1270]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="6.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="4.0">4–9</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DB9BFB2DFBB3B1B6" box="[984,1031,1245,1270]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5</number>
: 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DC52FB2DFB88B1B6" box="[1041,1084,1245,1270]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
(
<tableCitation id="EF5E9EC0FFC81B71DC09FB2DFB2AB1B6" box="[1098,1182,1245,1270]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1275,234,772]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Species of Zalmoxis with tarsomere counts that differ from the most common tarsal formula 3: 5 – 9: 5: 6 (deviations are shown in bold)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/F6A3FBF3FFCB1B72D8D4FF68FE56B58F" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" tableUuid="F6A3FBF3FFCB1B72D8D4FF68FE56B58F">
Table 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DCD2FB2EFB2AB1B6" box="[1169,1182,1246,1270]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). The presence of five tarsomeres on leg IV, supposedly diagnostic for 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DAF1FAF1FC93B059" box="[690,807,1281,1305]" class="Arachnida" family="Samoidae" genus="Fijicolana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DAF1FAF1FC93B059" box="[690,807,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Fijicolana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is currently shared by 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71DC6EFAF2FBFCB05A" box="[1069,1096,1282,1306]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="11.0">11</number>
other 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DCCCFAF1FB42B059" box="[1167,1270,1281,1305]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DCCCFAF1FB42B059" box="[1167,1270,1281,1305]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<tableCitation id="EF5E9EC0FFC81B71DD1FFAF1FF10B07E" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[159,1275,234,772]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Species of Zalmoxis with tarsomere counts that differ from the most common tarsal formula 3: 5 – 9: 5: 6 (deviations are shown in bold)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/F6A3FBF3FFCB1B72D8D4FF68FE56B58F" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" tableUuid="F6A3FBF3FFCB1B72D8D4FF68FE56B58F">
Table 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D8D4FAD6FF10B07E" box="[151,164,1318,1342]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). Therefore the presence of a scopula remains as the only diagnostic feature of 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DC6FFAD5FB15B07D" box="[1068,1185,1317,1341]" class="Arachnida" family="Samoidae" genus="Fijicolana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DC6FFAD5FB15B07D" box="[1068,1185,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Fijicolana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that would separate it from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71D9CEFAB9FE40B021" box="[397,500,1353,1377]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71D9CEFAB9FE40B021" box="[397,500,1353,1377]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Given that molecular evidence supports the monophyly of 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DCDAFAB9FAB4B021" box="[1177,1280,1353,1377]" class="Arachnida" family="Zalmoxidae" genus="Zalmoxis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DCDAFAB9FAB4B021" box="[1177,1280,1353,1377]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">Zalmoxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Pacific Islands, and that scopulae on tarsi III and IV are recurrently observed in unrelated lineages (
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DCE6FA9EFB7AB0C5" box="[1189,1230,1390,1413]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">e.g.</emphasis>
Ibaloniinae; Kury 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D8D4FA62FF66B0EA" box="[151,210,1426,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2007.0">2007</number>
, Sharma &amp; Giribet 
<number id="1414B95CFFC81B71D9E8FA62FE52B0EA" box="[427,486,1426,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" value="2011.0">2011</number>
), the scopula alone is insufficient to support 
<taxonomicName id="65DCD0F8FFC81B71DB94FA62FBC6B0E9" box="[983,1138,1425,1449]" class="Arachnida" family="Samoidae" genus="Fijicolana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="1" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="90A87769FFC81B71DB94FA62FBC6B0E9" box="[983,1138,1425,1449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="254">F. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as belonging to a genus of its own and instead is regarded as a putative autapomorphy of this species.
</paragraph>
